title: For Sale:  Remington 870 Police magnum
postcontent: At the begining of this year, I bought a Vang Comp Systems custom Remington 870 Police Magnum. This is a beautiful shotgun and I sadly haven't even shot it yet. It pains me to sell this beauty, but bills need paid and the wife said something had to go. I paid $1,395 plus shipping. I know I'm not going to get that, so I'll take $1,000.00 obo.The really nice thing about the shell carrier is the SN isn't covered, like with mose side shell carriers.The action on this gun is smooth, the over sized safety is a great feature, and the follower spring is strong.Ben at Boresight Solutions brought them in on trade, selected the best ones, then sent them to Vang Comp for an armorer level inspection and overhaul where necessary. Vang Comp then delivered the works: -Full VCS barrel port/backbore mod;-Vang Comp Ghost ring/picatinny rear sight and front night sight;-Oversize speed safety;-Deluxe DSAC w/extra Velcro shell carrier;-Vang Comp +2 magazine extension kit;-New factory hardwood furniture;-Graphite black Cerakote.He did not have the anodized aluminum trigger guards refinished, as in his experience the aluminum is often pitted and rough under the anodizing and looks worse Cerakoted than if left alone.According to Ben, "these guns seemed lightly used based on their internal condition when I picked them out; they were NOT the usual trash can police trade-ins you see that have been abused and damaged." Just to be clear, these are real Police Magnums, not one of the many cheaper versions (Tactical, Marine Magnum, etc) based on the 870 Express platform.

title: For Sale:  Gorgeous nickel plated Smith & Wesson Model 49 Bodyguard
postcontent: This beautiful and hard to find Smith & Wesson Model 49 Bodyguard was purchased by me from the liquidation of the estate of a deceased police officer. The officer owned a huge collection of various type guns, so none of them saw much use. This particular revolver was fired on a few special outings, but never carried, and was eventually stored in a protective gun rug until it was sold.The serial number indicates this gun to be of late 1976-early 1977 vintage. It is a S&W factory nickel plated steel .38 Special with a 2" pinned barrel, shrouded hammer, and five shot capacity. The gun is striking to admire, but it is also a wonderful shooter. I took it out to the gun range and put 25 rounds through it (have to shoot all of the vintage guns!) I was so impressed with both the single and double action trigger pull and accuracy. I can see why these Model 49's with the shrouded hammer were such popular carry conceal weapons by law enforcement officers.As was the case with many officer owned revolvers back then, this gun had its original grips taken off at initial purchase at an officer-frequented gun shop, discarded as many thousands were, and replaced with different grips. Those custom grips eventually found their way to a different revolver owned by the officer and another set of wood grips were put on this gun. I thought those grips were functional but not attractive, so I replaced them with some S&W grips I purchased so it now has the grips you see in the attached pictures that are nice but not numbered to the gun.This gun is in very nice condition. As with any nickel plated gun that has been shot or stored, there are a few handling marks on the gun but none that take away from its brilliant shine and eye appeal. The bore and chambers are bright, shiny, and clean. It is much too pretty for me to carry conceal, so I will carry a couple of S&W revolvers that have "more character" and won't mind a few more carry marks. In fact, I bought a blued and much less pristine condition Model 49 to use as part of my S&W revolver conceal carry rotation. This Model 49 will come enclosed in its very own Bore Stores fitted and treated gun rug.Before you go any further, please verify that you meet the following conditions and are willing and able to provide verifiable contact information in your initial correspondence."Able to complete at this time a local face-to-face cash sale. Buyer must be at least 21, Oklahoma resident able to legally buy a firearm in Oklahoma, and must have a current valid Oklahoma issued picture ID. No exceptions."
